(23, 11, 'Kyra Clark', 'Law Clerk', 'files/W53SqoAkrHG1xdNXcV6kxcEKnftiYs12giBbdNo3.jpg', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom: 18.75pt; text-align: justify; line-height: normal; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.5pt;font-family:Roboto;\nmso-fareast-font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;mso-bidi-font-family:Arial;\ncolor:#404040;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-themetint:191;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:\n#404040;mso-style-textfill-fill-themecolor:text1;mso-style-textfill-fill-alpha:\n100.0%;mso-style-textfill-fill-colortransforms:&quot;lumm=75000 lumo=25000&quot;;\nmso-font-kerning:0pt;mso-ligatures:none\">Kyra Clark is a rising 3L at Atlanta’s\nJohn Marshall Law School and will be sitting for the July 2023 bar examination.\nAfter pursuing her undergraduate degree in Political Science at the University\nof Central Florida, she moved to Atlanta, Georgia and decided to attend law\nschool for her J.D.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom: 18.75pt; text-align: justify; line-height: normal; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.5pt;font-family:Roboto;\nmso-fareast-font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;mso-bidi-font-family:Arial;\ncolor:#404040;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-themetint:191;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:\n#404040;mso-style-textfill-fill-themecolor:text1;mso-style-textfill-fill-alpha:\n100.0%;mso-style-textfill-fill-colortransforms:&quot;lumm=75000 lumo=25000&quot;;\nmso-font-kerning:0pt;mso-ligatures:none\">While in undergrad, she became\ninvolved in multiple organizations focused on immigration and refugee rights.\nAfter moving to Atlanta, Kyra began working as a family immigration paralegal\nfor a boutique law firm, where she gained a wealth of knowledge related to both\nfamily and employment immigration. While in law school, Kyra interned for\nTahirih Justice Center, a non-profit that supports immigrant survivors of human\ntrafficking, domestic violence, and victims of criminal activity. She has also\nworked as an immigration law clerk for Hall Booth Smith, P.C., a full-service\nnational law firm.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom: 18.75pt; text-align: justify; line-height: normal; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.5pt;font-family:Roboto;\nmso-fareast-font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;mso-bidi-font-family:Arial;\ncolor:#404040;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-themetint:191;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:\n#404040;mso-style-textfill-fill-themecolor:text1;mso-style-textfill-fill-alpha:\n100.0%;mso-style-textfill-fill-colortransforms:&quot;lumm=75000 lumo=25000&quot;;\nmso-font-kerning:0pt;mso-ligatures:none\">Kyra was born in Pune, India and came\nto the United States at a young age, therefore, she recognizes there are many\nchallenges that immigrants face when resettling. Due to this, she has made\nimmigration and refugee rights a pivotal focus in her career aspirations. She\nloves working in immigration law because she recognizes each client has their\nown story and aspirations and wants to assist them in achieving their goals by\nproviding competent legal services based on her extensive background in\nimmigration law.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\"><span style=\"font-size:19.0pt;